<DOC><DOCNO> AP880711-0038 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 0635EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-11 0579</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather ,0594</SECOND><HEAD>Disappointing Rain in Drought-Battered Midwest</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Showers and thunderstorms packing winds up to 58 mph coveredsections of the Northeast, the Midwest and the Southwest todayafter disappointingly small rains fell in the drought-batteredMidwest.   A flash flood watch was in effect for much of west Texas, whererain was very heavy in some places. Nearly an inch of rain fell injust one hour near Pandale in southwest Texas.   Showers and thunderstorms also fell in southern Arizona, easternOhio, western Pennsylvania, northern Nebraska and parts ofMissouri. At Cleveland's Lakefront Airport, winds gusted to 58 mph.   The storms Sunday in parts of the Midwest left less than aquarter of an inch of rain in most of Illinois, Indiana and lowerMichigan. Chicago received only a trace of rain.   A few farmers got a break. An inch of rain fell at Sheridan,Ind., and more than an inch fell at Alpena, Mich.   Showers and thunderstorms dissipated late Sunday over Florida,the Gulf Coast states, the Carolinas, the Tennessee Valley and theRockies.   In Michigan, a gust from a severe thunderstorm Sunday collapsedDome World, an indoor softball and golf driving range complex inGrand Rapids. In Belding, where the Gus Macker BasketballTournament was being played, one person was injured by lightningand another was hurt by falling tree limbs. All the backboards,each weighing 1,200 pounds, were knocked down.   Two people were struck by lightning in Bay County, Mich., whiletrying to cover a boat, authorities said.   In High Point, N.C., a severe thunderstorm knocked over atwo-story cinder-block wall of a building under construction, andblew a roof off a K mart being built down the road. The roof landedon cars in an adjacent parking lot.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from theEast Coast to the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the Gulf Coast statesand the southern Plains, with showers and thunderstorms mostnumerous over northern New England and the upper Ohio Valley;widely scattered showers and thunderstorms over the Rockies; andshowers in the Pacific Northwest.   High temperatures were forecast for the 70s in the upper GreatLakes region, the upper Mississippi Valley and the northern Plains;the 60s and 70s in the Pacific Northwest and along the Californiacoast; more than 100 degrees in the desert Southwest andCalifornia's central valleys; unseasonably high temperatures in themid- to upper 90s in the middle and north Atlantic Coast states;and 80s and and 90s elsewhere.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 46degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 94 degrees at NellisAir Force Base in Nevada.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 75 fair; Boston 78 fair; Buffalo 76 cloudy;Charleston, S.C. 77 cloudy; Cincinnati 71 foggy; Cleveland 70foggy; Detroit 69 foggy; Miami 82 fair; New York 75 foggy;Philadelphia 78 hazy; Pittsburgh 74 showers; Portland, Maine 66foggy; Washington 79 hazy.   _Central: Bismarck 55 fair; Chicago 68 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth76 partly cloudy; Denver 63 fair; Des Moines 68 fair; Indianapolis71 hazy; Kansas City 70 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 64 partlycloudy; Nashville 80 cloudy; New Orleans 79 partly cloudy; St.Louis 79 cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 67 fair; Anchorage 60 cloudy; Las Vegas 93windy; Los Angeles 64 cloudy; Phoenix 85 cloudy; Salt Lake City 78partly cloudy; San Diego 65 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle56 partly cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 75 cloudy; Toronto 72 hazy.</TEXT></DOC>